      "output": "\n\n# Why Is the Sky Blue?\n\nThis is a great question! The blue color of our sky is due to a phenomenon called **Rayleigh scattering**.\n\nHere's how it works:\n\n1. **Sunlight contains all colors** (red, orange, yellow, green, blue, violet) \u2014 which together appear white.\n\n2. **Earth's atmosphere** is made up of gases and tiny particles.\n\n3. When sunlight enters the atmosphere, it collides with air molecules and gets **scattered** in all directions.\n\n4. **Shorter wavelengths scatter more easily.** Blue light has a shorter wavelength than red light, so it scatters about **10 times more efficiently**.\n\n5. This scattered blue light reaches our eyes from all directions, making the sky appear blue.\n\n## Why Not Violet?\n\nYou might wonder why it's not violet, since violet has an even shorter wavelength. A couple of reasons:\n\n- Our eyes are less sensitive to violet\n- Some violet light is absorbed by the upper atmosphere\n\n## The Sky at Sunset\n\nAt sunrise and sunset, the sun's light travels through more atmosphere. Most of the blue light gets scattered away before reaching us, leaving mostly reds and oranges \u2014 which is why sunsets appear red or orange!\n\nThis effect was first explained by Lord Rayleigh in the 1870s.\n\nIs there anything else you'd like to know about this topic?",
